{"actual_usd":0.159605,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":255,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31156,"reply":"\"No, I don't think that works.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the square where the morning light is catching on the well chain, buying half a beat to say it cleanly.* \"If the resurrection was only a vision or an inner transformation, then Christianity starts coming apart right at the center.\"\n\n*I rest my forearms on my knees.* \"The whole claim is that Jesus actually rose — not just that the disciples felt renewed or had a powerful spiritual experience. If death wasn't really defeated in the flesh, then you've got inspiration, maybe, but not resurrection. And the earliest Christians seemed pretty committed to the scandalous version, the one that gets you mocked.\"\n\n\"Also...\" *I tip my head a little.* \"A grief vision explains one person better than it explains a whole movement staking everything on 'He is risen' in that concrete way. Not perfectly, sure. But I think the literal event makes better sense of the boldness, the empty-tomb kind of preaching, and the fact that they didn't talk like men preserving a meaningful metaphor.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench.* \"You asking because you're weighing the history of it, or the theology of what would follow if it were only inward?\"","rolling_24h_usd":62.60682500000001,"run_id":"2e4d1d74-28d7-4a03-b595-73f11c2f5a41"}
